    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-03-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-03-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="173"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d173">
                <head>173. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_KRW2" type="from">Robert W.
                        Komer</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d173fn0"
                        >Source: <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> Library, National
                        Security Files, Countries Series, Saudi Arabia, 1/63–3/63. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-03-01">March 1, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">McGB—</p>
                <p>Some of our spies are beginning to get quite worried about risk that Kurdish
                    problem may flare up again to bedevil new Iraqi regime. It’s hard to tell
                    whether talks in Baghdad are going well or badly, but there are many—Turks,
                    Iranians, <persName corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName>, and above all
                    Soviets—who might <pb facs="0448" n="382" xml:id="pg_382"/> see a stake in
                    egging Kurds on. We’re warning Iranians especially to keep hands off, but if
                    Shah should decide that new Iraq regime is too cozy with <persName
                        corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName>, he may not take our advice. I’ve urged
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> to raise contingency planning issue in
                    Special Group next time and hope you will support their pitch. Preventive
                    diplomacy is what we need most.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> is worried, <gloss target="#t_DIA1"
                        >DIA</gloss> less so, over growing possibility of <persName
                        corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName> ground strike into Saudi Arabia. State
                    thinks this unlikely on balance (<persName corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName>
                    unwilling to risk break with us), but I see <persName corresp="#p_NGA1"
                        >Nasser</persName> as testing us. Have urged Pentagon in any case to
                    consider preventive or subsequent military counters. Have also ginned up a
                    proposed third JFK warning to <persName corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName>
                    which should be over shortly. I’m hopeful <persName corresp="#p_NGA1"
                        >Nasser</persName> won’t escalate this far but we ought to be ready for a
                    painful decision.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KRW2">
                            <hi rend="strong">Bob K</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
